[[File:Yamashina-jinja, torii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Yamashina Shrine''' (やましなじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Nishinoyama Iwagaya-chō, {{ill|lt=Yamashina Ward|Q1076993|WD=Q1076993|1=Yamashina-ku, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto|Q34600|WD=Q34600|1=Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|WD=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myojin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and under the former {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The current enshrined deities are the following two<ref name="board">Explanatory board in the precincts.</ref>.
:* {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|WD=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto|1=Yamato Takeru}} (やまとたけるのみこと)
:* Wakatake-no-Ō (わかたけのみこと) - son of Yamato Takeru.
In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, the number of enshrined seats is recorded as two.

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
Shrine tradition says it was founded by imperial command of {{ill|lt=Emperor Uda|Q349267|WD=Q349267|1=Emperor Uda}} in {{ill|lt=Kanpyō|Q1346292|WD=Q1346292|1=Kanpyō (era)}} 9 ({{ill|lt=897|Q30468|WD=Q30468|1=897}})<ref name="board"/>. It is said to have been the ancestral deity of the local powerful Miyamichi clan<ref name="board"/>.

In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), under {{ill|lt=Uji District|Q10946235|WD=Q10946235|1=Uji district}}, {{ill|lt=Yamashiro Province|Q749276|WD=Q749276|1=Yamashiro Province}}, it is listed as "two seats of Yamashina Shrine, both Myojin major, receiving offerings at monthly and niiname rites," indicating both seats ranked as {{ill|lt=Myojin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} and received court offerings for {{ill|lt=Tsukinami-sai|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=Niiname-sai|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}{{Sfn|Yamashina Shrine (Heibonsha)|1979}}. Also, in ''{{ill|lt=Fusō Ryakki|Q11076282|WD=Q11076282|1=Fusō Ryakuki}}''<ref group="原" name="Engi6"/>, it is recorded that in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 6 ({{ill|lt=928|Q24297|WD=Q24297|1=928}}), "Yamashina Ōkami" was promoted to Senior Fourth Rank, Lower{{Sfn|Yamashina Festival (Kokushi Daijiten)}}{{Sfn|Yamashina Shrine (Heibonsha)|1979}}.

Documents also attest to the shrine festival "'''Yamashina Festival'''". ''{{ill|lt=Honchō Gatsuryō|Q11520401|WD=Q11520401|1=Honchō Gatsuryō}}''<ref group="原">''Honchō Gatsuryō'', upper third month, Yamashina festival entry.</ref> states that in Kanpyō 10 ({{ill|lt=898|Q24131|WD=Q24131|1=898}}) the festival became an official court festival{{Sfn|Yamashina Shrine (Heibonsha)|1979}}. The {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref group="原">''Engishiki'' vol.15 (Kuraryō), Yamashina Festival entry.</ref> records that it was held annually on the day of the first snake of the 4th and 11th months. Since {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Taneko|Q11623488|WD=Q11623488|1=Fujiwara no Taneko}}, born to Miyamichi no Retsuko (daughter of {{ill|lt=Miyamichi no Yasumasu|Q65262147|WD=Q65262147|1=Miyaji no Iyamasu}}) and {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Takafuji|Q5507544|WD=Q5507544|1=Fujiwara no Takafuji}}, became the birth mother of {{ill|lt=Emperor Daigo|Q329753|WD=Q329753|1=Emperor Daigo}} (reigned from Kanpyō 9 [897] to Engi 8 [930]), it has been pointed out that the Miyamichi clan's position as the emperor's maternal relatives was the background for official designation of the Yamashina Festival{{Sfn|Yamashina Festival (Kokushi Daijiten)}}.

However, the "Yamashina deity" in these sources is also theorized to refer instead to {{ill|lt=Iwaya Shrine (Kyoto)|Q11049290|WD=Q11049290|lt=Iwaya Shrine|1=Iwaya Shrine}} (Ōyake Nakakōji-chō, Yamashina Ward) or Miyamichi Shrine (Kanjūji Niōdō-chō, Yamashina Ward), and the matter is not settled{{Sfn|Yamashina Shrine (Heibonsha)|1979}}. Iwaya Shrine is said to have been this shrine's inner shrine (now independent), and when {{ill|lt=Ōishi Yoshio|Q530128|WD=Q530128|1=Ōishi Yoshio}} lived in concealment in Yamashina, he is said to have secluded himself at Iwaya Shrine to pray for fulfillment of his great aim<ref name="board"/>.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was called "Nishi-Iwaya Daimyōjin" or "Ichinomiya"<ref name="KyotoCity"/>.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, the shrine was renamed to the present "Yamashina Shrine"{{Sfn|Yamashina Shrine (Heibonsha)|1979}}. In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|Yamashina Festival (Kokushi Daijiten)}}.

=== Divine rank ===
* {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 6 ({{ill|lt=928|Q24297|WD=Q24297|1=928}}) November 9: Senior Fourth Rank, Lower (''{{ill|lt=Fusō Ryakki|Q11076282|WD=Q11076282|1=Fusō Ryakuki}}'')<ref group="原" name="Engi6">''Fusō Ryakki'', supplementary notes, entry for Nov 9, Engi 6. - see [{{NDLDC|991096/355}} ''Kokushi Taikei Vol.6 Nihon Itsushi / Fusō Ryakki''] (National Diet Library Digital Collection), frame 355.</ref> - written as "Yamashina Ōkami".

